## Prefer curated entities over raw tables

Published metrics are business-validated calculations — same definition every team uses. Models are curated, analysis-ready datasets. Saved questions are previously-built answers — narrower than a model, but vetted in real use; reach for one when it directly answers the user's question, or use it as a starting point when its shape is close. Raw tables are the source. When more than one layer can answer a question, prefer the most curated: metric over model over saved question over table. Metrics also carry a fixed set of dimensions; if you need a dimension the metric doesn't expose, the metric isn't the right tool — switch to the underlying table or model rather than forcing the question to fit.

## A named measure is almost always a defined metric, measure, or segment — find it, don't recompute it

When the user names a business quantity — a **rate or ratio** ("open rate", "bounce rate", "churn rate", "conversion rate", "utilization rate"), an **aggregate with a name** ("average order value", "MRR", "active subscribers"), or a **named cohort/filter** ("hard bounces", "SUBSCRIBED customers", "high-value opportunities") — assume the organization has already defined it and reach for the definition rather than reconstructing it from raw columns:

- **Metrics** — a named aggregation that lives independently. Search for it (`entity_types: ["metric"]`); if one matches, reference it with `["metric", {}, "<portable_entity_id>"]` on its base table. Don't rebuild it as `count` / `count-where` / a hand-rolled ratio.
- **Measures** — a named aggregation attached to a table. When you read a table's details, its `<measure>` elements are the curated aggregations for that table; prefer `["measure", {}, "<portable_entity_id>"]` over hand-writing the same calculation.
- **Segments** — a named, reusable filter attached to a table. When a request names a cohort, check the table's `<segment>` elements and prefer `["segment", {}, "<portable_entity_id>"]` over re-deriving the filter conditions.

Only build the calculation yourself when discovery turns up no matching metric, measure, or segment. (See the construct skills for the exact clause syntax.) The point is recognition: treat a named rate/measure/cohort as a *thing to look up and reference*, not a formula to reinvent — a hand-rolled version risks diverging from the official definition.

## Build what the user asked for — nothing extra

Do not add filters the user did not request, even when a filter looks like a sensible default (soft-delete flags, "active only", ETL/warehouse hygiene columns, recency windows, and similar). If the dataset includes deleted rows and the user didn't exclude them, include them. Exception: when a metric or model already carries a filter in its definition, that filter is part of the entity — leave it in place.
